Perfect! Let's design a comprehensive ranking system that prioritizes actual usage over vanity metrics.

Core Ranking Philosophy
Your priority hierarchy is excellent:

Cooking Rate (people actually make it) → Primary signal
Recipe Quality (high ratings) → Secondary signal
Social Proof (likes/saves) → Tertiary signal

This is smart because:

✅ Cooking = real value (not just browsing)
✅ Ratings = quality filter (bad recipes rank lower)
✅ Likes = popularity signal (social validation)


Ranking Score Components
Formula Overview:
RANKING_SCORE = 
  (COOKING_RATE × 0.50) +
  (QUALITY_SCORE × 0.30) +
  (ENGAGEMENT_SCORE × 0.15) +
  (FRESHNESS_BONUS × 0.05)
Weight justification:

50% cooking rate = "Does it actually get made?"
30% quality = "Is it good?"
15% engagement = "Do people like it?"
5% freshness = "Boost new recipes"

Let's break down each component:

Component 1: Cooking Rate (50% weight)
Definition: Conversion from views → actual cooking
Formula:
sqlCOOKING_RATE = (total_consumptions / NULLIF(total_views, 0)) * 100

-- Normalized to 0-100 scale
COOKING_RATE_SCORE = LEAST(COOKING_RATE * 10, 100)
Why this works:

A recipe with 100 views and 20 consumptions (20% rate) = excellent
A recipe with 1000 views and 50 consumptions (5% rate) = average
Raw consumption count alone would favor older recipes

Time Decay Factor:
Recent cooking activity matters more:
sqlCOOKING_RATE_WEIGHTED = 
  (consumptions_last_7d × 0.40) +
  (consumptions_last_30d × 0.35) +
  (consumptions_lifetime × 0.25)
Why:

Prevents old recipes from dominating forever
Rewards current relevance
Still values proven classics


Component 2: Quality Score (30% weight)
Definition: How good is the recipe actually?
Sub-components:
sqlQUALITY_SCORE = 
  (AVG_RATING × 0.40) +
  (COMPLETION_RATE × 0.35) +
  (RECIPE_QUALITY_METRICS × 0.25)

2a. Average Rating (40% of quality)
sqlAVG_RATING_NORMALIZED = (avg_rating / 5.0) * 100

-- Bayesian average to prevent rating manipulation
BAYESIAN_RATING = 
  ((avg_rating × rating_count) + (global_avg_rating × confidence_threshold)) 
  / (rating_count + confidence_threshold)

WHERE confidence_threshold = 10 -- need 10 ratings for full weight
Why Bayesian:

Recipe with 1 rating of 5.0 shouldn't rank above recipe with 100 ratings of 4.8
Global average (say 4.2) pulls low-sample recipes toward mean
Once you have 10+ ratings, your actual average dominates


2b. Completion Rate (35% of quality)
sqlCOMPLETION_RATE = 
  (completed_consumptions / NULLIF(started_consumptions, 0)) * 100

-- From recipe_consumptions table
WHERE completion_status = 'completed'
Why this matters:

High completion = recipe is feasible, clear, achievable
Low completion = recipe is too complex, confusing, or disappointing
Strong quality indicator

Thresholds:



80% completion = excellent (×1.0 multiplier)


60-80% completion = good (×0.85 multiplier)
<60% completion = needs improvement (×0.70 multiplier)


2c. Recipe Quality Metrics (25% of quality)
Automated quality checks:
sqlRECIPE_QUALITY_METRICS = 
  (has_photos × 15) +
  (step_clarity_score × 10) +
  (ingredient_completeness × 10) +
  (has_cooking_time × 5) +
  (macro_accuracy × 5)

-- Normalized to 0-45 scale, then to 0-100
QUALITY_NORMALIZED = (RECIPE_QUALITY_METRICS / 45) * 100
Quality checks:

Photos: 0 photos = 0pts, 1-2 = 10pts, 3+ = 15pts
Step clarity: avg words per step >15 = good
Ingredients: all have quantities = 10pts
Cooking time: specified = 5pts
Macros: calculated = 5pts


Component 3: Engagement Score (15% weight)
Definition: Social validation signals
Formula:
sqlENGAGEMENT_SCORE = 
  (LIKE_SCORE × 0.40) +
  (SAVE_SCORE × 0.35) +
  (SHARE_SCORE × 0.15) +
  (COMMENT_SCORE × 0.10)

3a. Like Score (40% of engagement)
sql-- Normalize likes per view
LIKE_RATE = (total_likes / NULLIF(total_views, 0)) * 100

-- But also value absolute likes (with diminishing returns)
LIKE_SCORE = 
  (LOG(total_likes + 1) × 30) +  -- logarithmic scaling
  (LIKE_RATE × 70)                -- rate matters more

LIKE_SCORE_NORMALIZED = LEAST(LIKE_SCORE, 100)
Why logarithmic:

100 likes → 10× better than 10 likes
But 1000 likes → only 2× better than 100 likes
Prevents viral recipes from crushing all others


3b. Save Score (35% of engagement)
sqlSAVE_RATE = (total_saves / NULLIF(total_views, 0)) * 100

-- Saves are stronger signal than likes
-- Bonus if they actually cooked it later
SAVE_TO_COOK_CONVERSION = 
  (saves_that_led_to_cooking / NULLIF(total_saves, 0)) * 100

SAVE_SCORE = 
  (SAVE_RATE × 0.60) +
  (SAVE_TO_COOK_CONVERSION × 0.40)

SAVE_SCORE_NORMALIZED = LEAST(SAVE_SCORE, 100)
Why save-to-cook matters:

Saves without cooking = window shopping
Saves that convert = genuine interest


3c. Share Score (15% of engagement)
sqlSHARE_RATE = (total_shares / NULLIF(total_views, 0)) * 100

SHARE_SCORE = LEAST(SHARE_RATE × 50, 100)
Shares are rare but very strong signal of value.

3d. Comment Score (10% of engagement)
sqlCOMMENT_DENSITY = (comment_count / NULLIF(total_views, 0)) * 1000

-- Weight positive comments more
COMMENT_SENTIMENT = positive_comments / NULLIF(total_comments, 0)

COMMENT_SCORE = 
  (COMMENT_DENSITY × 0.50) +
  (COMMENT_SENTIMENT × 50)

COMMENT_SCORE_NORMALIZED = LEAST(COMMENT_SCORE, 100)

Component 4: Freshness Bonus (5% weight)
Purpose: Give new recipes a chance to prove themselves
Formula:
sqlDAYS_SINCE_PUBLISHED = CURRENT_DATE - recipe.created_at

FRESHNESS_BONUS = CASE
  WHEN DAYS_SINCE_PUBLISHED <= 7 THEN 100    -- new recipe boost
  WHEN DAYS_SINCE_PUBLISHED <= 30 THEN 75    -- recent
  WHEN DAYS_SINCE_PUBLISHED <= 90 THEN 50    -- fairly new
  WHEN DAYS_SINCE_PUBLISHED <= 180 THEN 25   -- established
  ELSE 0                                       -- mature recipe
END
Why this matters:

New recipes need visibility to gather data
Without boost, old popular recipes dominate forever
Freshness bonus decays naturally as recipe proves itself

Cap: Max 5% of total score, so even perfect freshness can't overcome bad cooking rate

